fields.description:
We've observed that any EyeQL queries which include a "group by" clause will fail to display the second or subsequent pages because the server fails to respond. When display parameters are included, this behavior extends to the csv output results as well.


Consider the second page of the query...
{quote}
select revisions where date in (2009-01-01, today) group by changeset
{quote}

The URL for the second page of the query results (shown below against svn.atlassian.com) fails to return a response from the server.

{code}

% curl --verbose 'http://svn.atlassian.com/fisheye/search/public/?ql=select%20revisions%20where%20date%20in%20%282009-01-01%2Ctoday%29%20group%20by%20changeset%0D%0A&spage=2'
* About to connect() to svn.atlassian.com port 80 (#0)
*   Trying 63.246.22.202... connected
* Connected to svn.atlassian.com (63.246.22.202) port 80 (#0)
> GET /fisheye/search/public/?ql=select%20revisions%20where%20date%20in%20%282009-01-01%2Ctoday%29%20group%20by%20changeset%0D%0A&spage=2 HTTP/1.1
> User-Agent: curl/7.16.3 (powerpc-apple-darwin9.0) libcurl/7.16.3 OpenSSL/0.9.7l zlib/1.2.3
> Host: svn.atlassian.com
> Accept: */*
> 
* Empty reply from server
* Connection #0 to host svn.atlassian.com left intact
curl: (52) Empty reply from server
* Closing connection #0
{code}
fields.summary: EyeQL results which include "group by" clause disconnect when serving second page

fields.description:
Scenario:

    * Create area in Perforce and populate with changes. Make number of changes to files
    * In Fisheye add a Perforce repository and limit Fisheye's scanning to a change list after one of those files was last edited
          o File Foo was edited in changelist #12, other files were updated in changelist #13, limit scan to go back to #13

    * Scan area, file foo will not appear.
    * Edit and submit file foo: Will appear as an "add" instead of "edit"

This causes confusion as there is no way in Fisheye to tell there is a limit to how far back in history the repository goes.

Suggested Resolutions:

    * Add note in Fisheye to note "This repostory is limited changes made after change list # 12345678"
    * Change the Crucible Review note from "Added" in cases where an Edit is found to "Edit with no history" or some other marker
    * OR allow Fisheye to get the Revision (n-1) to get last revision if it does exist.
fields.summary: Fisheye shows files as "added" when they are an "Edit with no Fisheye history"

fields.description:
We frequently have to edit the config.xml by hand, for instance adding a new repository. This seems much safer than using the UI. Also we change the perforce server of existing repositories and restart, because when doing the initial indexing we point Fisheye at a backup perforce instance, to ease the load. If we change the server through the UI, it wants us to reindex (I think).

To make this easier for us, could Fisheye/Crucible:

# Have a button that allows re-reading the config.xml from disk, so we don't have to restart Fisheye.
#  pretty print the XML before writing it to disk (makes it easier to edit).

cheers
